Plastic Debris

Stuart Watt

Introduction and Setup

Im using the following packages:

knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.align="center")

library(tidyverse)
library(purrr)
library(magrittr)
library(treemap)
# library(data.tree)
# library(igraph)
# library(ggraph)
# library(DiagrammeR)

Logged marine debris is available for download here. Im importing data from 2010 till Feb 19th 2020. There doesnt seem to be data before 2010. The data is reported marine debris.

data <- list.files(path = "data/", full.names = TRUE) %>% 
  lapply(FUN = read_csv, col_types = "ififidddddcfcif") %>% 
  reduce(rbind)

A quick look at the data:

data

Exploratory Data Analysis

Lets first check for missing values:

data %>% select_if(function(x) any(is.na(x))) %>% colnames()
[1] "Location"    "Description"

So only these columns contain missing values. Lets see the amount of unique values for each column:

data %>% apply(2, function(x) length(unique(x)))
              ListID             ListName               ItemID 
                   1                    1                   55 
            ItemName                LogID             Latitude 
                  55               363368               142707 
           Longitude             Altitude             Quantity 
              136490               135214                  496 
        Error Radius            Timestamp             Location 
               18374               248436                 1458 
         Description          Material ID Material Description 
                8494                    8                    8

Both ListID and ListName dont give us any information, so we will remove them both.

data <- data %>% select(-ListID,-ListName)

Lets see if there are any ItemNames associated with more than one Material Descriptions.

# data %>% select(`Material Description`, ItemName) %>%
#   group_by(`Material Description`) %>% 
#   mutate(numberOf)
#   summarise(distinct)
data %>% select(`Material Description`, ItemName) %>%
  distinct() %$% 
  table(ItemName) %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  filter(n > 1)

So rubber gloves are associated with two material descriptions, but otherwise a one to many relationship exists between Material Description and ItemName.

data %>% select(`Material Description`, ItemName, Quantity) %>%
  filter(ItemName == "Rubber Gloves") %>% 
  group_by(`Material Description`) %>% 
  summarise(Quantity = sum(Quantity))

It seems that most rubber gloves are classified as plastic rather than rubber.

data %>% select(`Material Description`, ItemName, Description) %>%
  filter(ItemName == "Rubber Gloves", !is.na(Description)) %>% 
  distinct()

All non-missing descriptions of rubber gloves are in the described as plastic.

Distribution of observed debris:

data %>% select(Quantity,Description,`Material Description`) %>% 
  group_by(`Material Description`) %>% 
  summarise(Quantity = sum(Quantity)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(`Material Description`, Quantity), y = Quantity)) +
    geom_col() +
    ylab("Total recorded quantity") +
    xlab("Material class") +
    coord_flip()

A tree map of material quantities:

data %>% 
  select(`Material Description`, ItemName, Quantity) %>% 
  group_by(`Material Description`, ItemName) %>% 
  summarise(Quantity = sum(Quantity)) %>% 
  treemap(index = c("Material Description", "ItemName"),
          vSize = "Quantity", draw = TRUE)

Perhaps some of the debris is not actually from the sea, but rather from people littering by the coastline?

data %>% filter(`Material Description` == "PLASTIC") %>% 
  select(ItemName) %>% 
  group_by(ItemName) %>% 
  count(sort = TRUE)
